mit(ORDER_CREATED, ...)` starts, pushes to log, gets handlers, enters `for` loop, first handler runs synchronously, then `await handler(payload)` resolves — but actually `await void_return` creates a microtask\n3. `createOrder` returns orderId (synchronous)\n4. `await payment.processPayment(orderId, 50)` is called — `processPayment` is async, so it starts executing synchronously\n5. Inside `processPayment`, `await bus.emit(PAYMENT_PROCESSED, ...)` is called\n6. `bus.emit(PAYMENT_PROCESSED, ...)` starts synchronously — pushes to log, gets handlers, first handler runs\n7. The PAYMENT_PROCESSED handler looks up `orderTotals.get(event.orderId)` — but the ORDER_CREATED handler that sets orderTotals hasn't finished yet!\n\nThat's the bug. The `void` fire-and-forget means ORDER_CREATED handlers may not complete before PAYMENT_PROCESSED handlers run.\n\nThe fix: In the test, I need to wait for the ORDER_CREATED event to complete. Or better, I should look at whether the `createOrder` should use `await` on the emit. But the task says not to modify bus.ts. The issue is in orders/index.ts using `void bus.emit(...)`. \n\nActually wait — let me re-read the emit code. `bus.emit` is:\n```ts\nasync emit(event: string, payload: unknown): Promise<void> {\n    this.eventLog.push({ event, payload, timestamp: Date.now() });\n    const handlers = this.handlers.get(event);\n    if (handlers) {\n      for (const handler of handlers) {\n        await handler(payload);\n      }\n    }\n  }\n```\n\nThe first handler invocation runs synchronously until it returns. If the handler is synchronous (returns void, not Promise), then `await handler(payload)` evaluates handler(payload) synchronously (returning undefined), then `await undefined` creates a microtask boundary. So:\n\n- `bus.emit(ORDER_CREATED, ...)` pushes to log, gets handlers set, starts for loop\n- Handler 1 (analytics ORDER_CREATED handler) runs synchronously — sets orderTotals, etc.\n- `await handler(payload)` — handler returned void